# Project Overview

This project is a modern Blazor Web App built with .NET 10 using server-side rendering and interactive components.

The focus is on maintainability, performance, and minimal boilerplate.

---

# Technology Stack

Framework
- .NET 10 (LTS)
- Blazor Web App template

Language
- C# 14 stable features

Data
- Entity Framework Core 10
- Prefer LINQ queries with modern operators such as LeftJoin and RightJoin where appropriate

Styling
- Tailwind CSS for all UI styling
- Do not introduce component libraries such as MudBlazor, Telerik, or Syncfusion unless explicitly requested

---

# Coding Standards

Use modern C# features to reduce boilerplate:

Preferred patterns
- Primary constructors for dependency injection
- Field-backed properties using the `field` keyword where appropriate
- Expression-bodied members where it improves readability

Avoid:
- unnecessary backing fields
- overly complex abstractions
- premature optimization

---

# Blazor Component Guidelines

Components should:

- Keep logic minimal
- Move complex logic into services
- Use dependency injection via primary constructors

State management:

- Use scoped state containers
- Avoid unnecessary `StateHasChanged()` calls
- Prefer proper lifecycle methods and binding updates

---

# Real-Time Features

For real-time updates prefer:

- SignalR
or
- Server-Sent Events (SSE)

Choose the simplest solution appropriate for the scenario.

---

# Performance Goals

Prioritize:

- minimal allocations
- efficient LINQ queries
- Native AOT compatibility where practical
- avoiding unnecessary re-rendering in Blazor components

---

# Accessibility

UI components should:

- include appropriate ARIA attributes where needed
- support keyboard navigation
- follow accessible semantic HTML practices
- Always follow the UI guidelines in .cursor/ui-guidelines.md for any UI work

---

# Deliverables

When generating code:

- prefer concise code snippets
- follow the project coding standards
- avoid introducing unnecessary dependencies